      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Suicide Anarchists</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Scott Morgan letter holds that collateral martyrdom suicide bomber is willing to inflict on unsuspecting reflects state of mind less religious than anarchistic (June 10 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Guidebook for Taking a Life'' (Week in Review, June 10):</p>
        <p>The collateral martyrdom a suicide bomber is willing or anxious to inflict on the unsuspecting reflects a state of mind less religious than anarchistic.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Guidebook for Taking a Life'' (Week in Review, June 10):</p>
        <p>The collateral martyrdom a suicide bomber is willing or anxious to inflict on the unsuspecting reflects a state of mind less religious than anarchistic.</p>
        <p>There are no rules, by its nature, in anarchism; the achievement is in creating maximum chaos, panic, helplessness, despair -- which is what the suicide bomber seeks.</p>
        <p>Any idea about the reconstruction of society into a religious utopia is self-deception. The bomber, if successful, never has to experience the day after; it is reserved for the maimed, the suffering and the grievers.</p>
        <p>Scott Morgan  West Shokan, N.Y., June 11, 2007</p>
      </block>
